{"actual_usd":0.125265,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":251,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24300,"reply":"\"I don't know how to split those apart without breaking the thing itself.\" *I rub a thumb over a dry streak of clay on my apron, thinking a beat before I go on.* \"If Easter is only a fine symbol—new life, hope, all that—then it's a poem. A good one, maybe. But Christian faith hangs its coat on something that happened in the flesh. If the tomb wasn't empty, then we're not talking about resurrection; we're talking about sentiment wearing resurrection's clothes.\"\n\n*I glance toward the window where the morning light keeps shifting under the clouds.* \"Now—does it also mean more than the bare fact? Of course. Facts like that come with a sky full of meaning. But the meaning rides in on the event, not instead of it. That's always seemed to me the Christian scandal of it: not just 'death and sorrow can feel transformed,' but 'Christ really rose.'\"\n\n\"I'd put it plain: without the literal resurrection, you might still have a moving philosophy. You do not have Christianity in its full shape.\" *I tilt my head a little.* \"Are you asking because you're weighing the argument itself, or because you're feeling the pressure of what can still be believed honestly?\"","rolling_24h_usd":90.90502,"run_id":"0bd00feb-6940-4495-a7fc-24894385a77f"}
